    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-07-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-07-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="476"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d476">
                <head>476. Memorandum From the Secretary of State’s Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RFH1" type="from">Russell</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                        >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d476fn1">Source: Department of State, <gloss
                            target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss> Files: Lot 59 D 518, Omega—Memos, etc. fr
                        July 1 to August 31, 1956. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-07-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1956</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Contact with Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hussein</persName> this
                        Morning</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>He asserts on his personal honor that any belief that the Soviets have not
                        made a firm offer on the Aswan Dam is without any foundation. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SDT1">Shepilov</persName> made an offer to <persName
                            corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName> and it is “frighteningly
                        good.”</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName> is “hell-bent” to go ahead
                        with the Aswan project. He feels that it is a firm political commitment he
                        has made to the Egyptian people.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName> is very much worried about
                        accepting the Soviet offer for the following reasons: <list>
                            <label>a.</label>
                            <item>He is concerned over the growth of pro-Soviet sentiment in Egypt.
                                In the moving picture houses after <persName corresp="#p_SDT1"
                                    >Shepilov</persName>’s visit, when newsreels were shown of
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SDT1">Shepilov</persName> and also of
                                    <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName>, <persName
                                    corresp="#p_SDT1">Shepilov</persName> got much more applause
                                than <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName> did.</item>
                            <label>b.</label>
                            <item>The Soviets have not kept their word to him with respect to
                                secrecy on the offer which they made on the Aswan Dam.</item>
                            <label>c.</label>
                            <item>A number of his close advisers who have previously been urging him
                                to accept Soviet arms and other forms of Soviet cooperation are now
                                beginning to be worried over Egypt’s position as between the West
                                and the Soviet world.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hussein</persName> personally … hopes that we can
                        keep our offer open and then convert the undertaking into something more
                        practicable.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hussein</persName> asserts on his word of honor
                        and without any equivocation or condition that if the US–<gloss
                            target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss> offer
                        is not made firm, <persName corresp="#p_NNNCGA1">Nasser</persName> will
                        accept the Soviet offer.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
